WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:03.135 --> 00:00:05.271 align:start size:97% position:3%
David Vogelpohl: Hello,
everyone, and welcome back to

00:00:05.304 --> 00:00:07.607
WordPress Accessibility Day.

00:00:07.640 --> 00:00:11.344
My name is David Vogelpohl from
WP Engine, and I'm proud to be

00:00:11.377 --> 00:00:14.414
your host for the session
"Using Smart Speakers for

00:00:14.447 --> 00:00:17.250 align:start size:78% position:22%
Accessibility,"
with Chip Edwards.

00:00:17.283 --> 00:00:20.219
I'm honored to introduce Chip
in his session, "Using Smart

00:00:20.252 --> 00:00:22.121
Speakers for Accessibility."

00:00:22.154 --> 00:00:25.058
Chip is a partner at
CreateMyVoice.com.

00:00:25.091 --> 00:00:28.294
He helps content producers
engage audiences on smart

00:00:28.327 --> 00:00:31.597
speakers like Amazon
Alexa and Google Home.

00:00:31.630 --> 00:00:34.867 align:start size:94% position:6%
Chip is a teacher--hopefully
he's a good one today--a

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:38.671
speaker, and technologist who
is passionate about connecting

00:00:38.704 --> 00:00:42.642 align:start size:91% position:9%
WordPress content to
the new voice technology.

00:00:42.675 --> 00:00:46.412 align:start size:84% position:16%
Chip, welcome, and
glad to have you here.

00:00:46.445 --> 00:00:47.680 align:start size:84% position:16%
Chip Edwards: Thanks,
glad to be here

00:00:47.713 --> 00:00:49.782 align:start position:0%
and be able to
talk with us about the session.

00:00:49.815 --> 00:00:51.517
This is good stuff.

00:00:51.550 --> 00:00:52.852
David: Looking forward to it.

00:00:52.885 --> 00:00:54.620 align:start size:81% position:19%
Chip: Thanks, David.
I appreciate it.

00:00:54.653 --> 00:00:56.355
Ready for me to share my screen?

00:00:56.388 --> 00:00:58.458 align:start size:97% position:3%
David: Yes, sir, ready to go.
Let's get it goin'.

00:00:58.491 --> 00:01:00.359
Chip: Okay, let's see.

00:01:00.392 --> 00:01:02.128 align:start size:88% position:13%
David: I love your
background, by the way.

00:01:02.161 --> 00:01:04.263
Chip: Oh, thank you, heh-heh.

00:01:04.296 --> 00:01:07.400
Share computer sound 'cause
we're gonna do some today.

00:01:07.433 --> 00:01:08.835
Let's see.

00:01:08.868 --> 00:01:11.471 line:0%
Hopefully that is
up and runnin'.

00:01:11.504 --> 00:01:15.141 align:start position:0% line:0%
Okay, so we all care about
accessibility, including making

00:01:15.174 --> 00:01:18.611 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
our websites accessible
for the visually impaired.

00:01:18.644 --> 00:01:23.216 line:0%
Stuff like using header tags
properly, makin' sure that the

00:01:23.249 --> 00:01:26.219 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
alt text has
meaningful information.

00:01:26.252 --> 00:01:28.921 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
These are important so that
screen readers can

00:01:28.954 --> 00:01:31.591 line:0%
turn our text into audio.

00:01:31.624 --> 00:01:35.862 line:0%
But today I wanna focus on how
the adoption of smart speakers

00:01:35.895 --> 00:01:38.764 line:0%
is changing how we
think about design.

00:01:38.797 --> 00:01:41.701 align:start position:0% line:0%
If you think about it, smart
speakers are kind of like screen

00:01:41.734 --> 00:01:46.772 align:start position:0% line:0%
readers but more so because
the primary interaction with our

00:01:46.805 --> 00:01:50.243 line:0%
content is verbal
instead of visual.

00:01:50.276 --> 00:01:54.914 align:start position:0% line:0%
When thinking about voice-first
design, our mind-sets shift

00:01:54.947 --> 00:01:59.418 line:0%
because now we aren't talking
about doing something special

00:01:59.451 --> 00:02:00.920 line:0%
for the visually impaired.

00:02:00.953 --> 00:02:04.957 line:0%
With smart speakers, if your
content doesn't work well for

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:07.693 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
the visually impaired, it
doesn't work well for

00:02:07.726 --> 00:02:10.263 line:0%
anybody on the platform.

00:02:10.296 --> 00:02:12.665 line:0%
And before we get goin', I
want to acknowledge that

00:02:12.698 --> 00:02:16.769 line:0%
smart-speaker platforms are
not necessarily platforms for

00:02:16.802 --> 00:02:21.807 line:0%
accessibility, however, I wanna
show you how smart speakers are

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:26.479 line:0%
causing a significant shift
in our UI/UX design thoughts.

00:02:26.512 --> 00:02:30.850 align:start position:0% line:0%
Smart speakers are shifting
how we access compute resources.

00:02:30.883 --> 00:02:35.454 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
And I'm gonna be using
some smart speakers today.

00:02:35.487 --> 00:02:37.623 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
I'm actually recording some
of 'em, but it kind of doesn't

00:02:37.656 --> 00:02:38.958 line:0%
matter on your end.

00:02:38.991 --> 00:02:41.627 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
So now would be a good time
to un-mute your Amazon

00:02:41.660 --> 00:02:44.297 line:0%
or your Google device.

00:02:44.330 --> 00:02:45.998 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
Okay, there's three points
that I wanna cover in

00:02:46.031 --> 00:02:47.132 line:0%
the next few minutes.

00:02:47.166 --> 00:02:49.502 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
First, let's talk about
how smart speakers or voice

00:02:49.535 --> 00:02:52.438 line:0%
assistants make tasks easier.

00:02:52.471 --> 00:02:56.008 align:start position:0% line:0%
The goal is to reduce the
friction to getting stuff done,

00:02:56.041 --> 00:02:59.011 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
to make it easier to find
things, to turn things on or

00:02:59.044 --> 00:03:03.349 line:0%
off, to get directions, to hear
content, in essence, to make our

00:03:03.382 --> 00:03:07.453 line:0%
lives more convenient and to
make it easier to get computers

00:03:07.486 --> 00:03:09.322 line:0%
to do things for us.

00:03:09.355 --> 00:03:13.659 line:0%
Next, I wanna demonstrate what's
currently happening with voice

00:03:13.692 --> 00:03:17.530 line:0%
assistants, and then lastly,
I wanna give you some bonus

00:03:17.563 --> 00:03:21.400 line:0%
material around verbal branding
and why you may want to secure

00:03:21.433 --> 00:03:24.537 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
your verbal domain name
sooner as opposed to later.

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:25.972 line:0%
So let's get started.

00:03:26.005 --> 00:03:29.875 line:0%
Smart speakers come in many
shapes and sizes and from a

00:03:29.908 --> 00:03:31.611 line:0%
number of manufacturers.

00:03:31.644 --> 00:03:35.881 align:start position:0% line:0%
We're most familiar with
devices from Amazon and Google.

00:03:35.914 --> 00:03:39.819 line:0%
They've got, like, 85% of the
smart speakers out there, I

00:03:39.852 --> 00:03:42.555 line:0%
think, that are producing,
but there's many traditional

00:03:42.588 --> 00:03:46.525 line:0%
manufacturers of speakers as
well, and they're now making

00:03:46.558 --> 00:03:50.263 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
their speakers smart by
adding microphones to them and

00:03:50.296 --> 00:03:53.699 line:0%
connecting 'em up to one or more
of the digital voice assistants,

00:03:53.732 --> 00:03:58.037 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
almost always Amazon's or
Google's voice assistants, but

00:03:58.070 --> 00:03:59.538
there are a few
others out there.

00:03:59.571 --> 00:04:02.808 align:start size:97% position:3%
In a recent article on
Voicebot.ai, they reported on

00:04:02.841 --> 00:04:05.745 align:start size:97% position:3%
where people are
putting these smart speakers.

00:04:05.778 --> 00:04:09.081
While it used to be the living
room and the kitchen, now the

00:04:09.114 --> 00:04:14.420 align:start size:97% position:3%
bedroom is the most
popular location at over 45%.

00:04:14.453 --> 00:04:18.291 align:start size:97% position:3%
The living rooms got about
43%, and the kitchen with 41%.

00:04:18.324 --> 00:04:22.495
The numbers add up to more than
100% because people are--once

00:04:22.528 --> 00:04:25.798 align:start position:0%
they start using these devices,
they're finding them really

00:04:25.831 --> 00:04:28.701
convenient, and so they're
actually putting--they're

00:04:28.734 --> 00:04:31.070
actually purchasing multiple
smart speakers and putting 'em

00:04:31.103 --> 00:04:33.005
in a number of locations.

00:04:33.038 --> 00:04:37.076 align:start size:94% position:6%
By the way, now more than
13% are putting 'em in their

00:04:37.109 --> 00:04:39.011
bathroom as well.

00:04:39.044 --> 00:04:42.048 align:start position:0%
In an article titled "The Future
of Voice and the Implications

00:04:42.081 --> 00:04:45.418
for News," published for the
Reuters Institute, Nic Newman

00:04:45.451 --> 00:04:49.588 align:start position:0%
says, "Voice goes way
beyond smart speakers to become

00:04:49.621 --> 00:04:53.326 align:start position:0%
embedded in every device",
because the tech companies view

00:04:53.359 --> 00:04:55.861 align:start position:0%
these voice-assistant devices as
a way to support

00:04:55.894 --> 00:04:58.097
and anticipate user needs.

00:04:58.130 --> 00:05:01.434
These tech companies want to
have their voice assistants

00:05:01.467 --> 00:05:04.603
everywhere so they can
help us anywhere we are.

00:05:04.636 --> 00:05:08.107 align:start size:97% position:3%
In 2018, "The Wall Street
Journal" reported on Amazon's

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:10.109 align:start size:84% position:16%
direction for
their smart speakers.

00:05:10.142 --> 00:05:14.447
"Amazon had more than 10,000
employees working on its Amazon

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:18.150
Alexa virtual assistant at the
time, and they wanted to expand

00:05:18.183 --> 00:05:22.621
Alexa in the offices, cars, and
even hotel rooms," and they've

00:05:22.654 --> 00:05:26.759
got more locations that they're
actually working on right now.

00:05:26.792 --> 00:05:29.462
Matter of fact, have any of you
seen the latest Buick commercial

00:05:29.495 --> 00:05:34.033 align:start position:0%
where they're arguing over
whether it's an SUV or an Alexa?

00:05:34.066 --> 00:05:36.802
This idea of our voice
assistants being with us

00:05:36.835 --> 00:05:40.373
everywhere is actually
starting to materialize.

00:05:40.406 --> 00:05:43.943
Last year, Sundar Pichai, the
CEO of Google, said that he was

00:05:43.976 --> 00:05:48.414 align:start position:0%
"Moving Google from a company
that helps you find answers to a

00:05:48.447 --> 00:05:51.083
company that helps
you get things done."

00:05:51.116 --> 00:05:53.886 align:start size:97% position:3%
Subtle shift, but they're
changing that, and as you look

00:05:53.919 --> 00:05:57.456 align:start size:94% position:6%
at even the voice search
results, you see how they're

00:05:57.489 --> 00:05:59.625 align:start size:84% position:16%
actually making
some of those shifts.

00:05:59.658 --> 00:06:01.660 align:start size:81% position:19%
Well, it didn't
start off this way.

00:06:01.693 --> 00:06:04.397
Now the same voice assistant
that's found in your smart

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:09.101 align:start size:94% position:6%
speaker is also in your
smartphone and in your cars,

00:06:09.134 --> 00:06:12.805
and in the latest is in
wearables, like glasses

00:06:12.838 --> 00:06:14.940
frames or earbuds.

00:06:14.973 --> 00:06:17.143
My favorite place is
my earbuds actually.

00:06:17.176 --> 00:06:20.646
Now my voice assistant can be
with me anywhere, places like

00:06:20.679 --> 00:06:25.718
the gym, where I like to listen
to blogs and podcasts, and when

00:06:25.751 --> 00:06:29.221 align:start position:0%
I'm in the grocery stores,
shopping, and I can just ask for

00:06:29.254 --> 00:06:30.956 align:start size:78% position:22%
"Hey, what's on
my shopping list?"

00:06:30.989 --> 00:06:33.426 align:start size:94% position:6%
I'll be glad when they have
these voice assistants

00:06:33.459 --> 00:06:34.760
in every elevator.

00:06:34.793 --> 00:06:36.862 align:start size:81% position:19%
There's already a
computer waiting for

00:06:36.895 --> 00:06:38.497
somebody to touch the button.

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:40.132
Why do I have to
touch the button?

00:06:40.165 --> 00:06:42.668
Why doesn't the computer
just respond when I say,

00:06:42.701 --> 00:06:44.103
"Third floor, please"?

00:06:44.136 --> 00:06:47.706 align:start position:0%
I'm predicting that voice
technology will continue to get

00:06:47.739 --> 00:06:51.811 align:start position:0%
better, and soon, we'll start
relying on these devices because

00:06:51.844 --> 00:06:56.081
they make tasks easy, and then,
just like our smartphone, we

00:06:56.114 --> 00:06:59.885
won't know how we ever lived
without the voice assistant.

00:06:59.918 --> 00:07:03.189 align:start size:97% position:3%
So now I'd like to demonstrate
how companies are currently

00:07:03.222 --> 00:07:05.191
using voice technology.

00:07:05.224 --> 00:07:08.561
Most people are familiar with
using their voice assistant for

00:07:08.594 --> 00:07:11.230 align:start position:0%
things like turning on the
lights, adding items to shopping

00:07:11.263 --> 00:07:15.901
lists, getting the news or the
weather or navigation, actually,

00:07:15.934 --> 00:07:19.772
like letting Siri or Google
to find the best route home.

00:07:19.805 --> 00:07:23.576 align:start position:0%
But Google and Amazon have
made a way for companies to make

00:07:23.609 --> 00:07:28.013 align:start position:0%
these voice assistants
smarter by building a voice app.

00:07:28.046 --> 00:07:29.849
Amazon calls these
voice apps "skills."

00:07:29.882 --> 00:07:31.183
You may have heard that.

00:07:31.216 --> 00:07:32.985
Google calls these
voice apps "actions."

00:07:33.018 --> 00:07:34.954 align:start size:94% position:6%
I'll use the generic term of
"voice app" through

00:07:34.987 --> 00:07:36.188
the rest of this.

00:07:36.222 --> 00:07:39.258
But instead of me just telling
you what companies are doing, I

00:07:39.291 --> 00:07:41.660 align:start size:91% position:9%
figured it would be
better for me to show you.

00:07:41.693 --> 00:07:45.531
I just mentioned about using a
voice app to add capabilities to

00:07:45.564 --> 00:07:47.233
these voice-assistant devices.

00:07:47.266 --> 00:07:50.703
There's one new term
that you need to know.

00:07:50.736 --> 00:07:53.706 align:start size:97% position:3%
It's called "invocation name,"
sometimes referred to as a

00:07:53.739 --> 00:07:55.641
"verbal domain name."

00:07:55.674 --> 00:07:58.944 align:start position:0%
So just like your website has a
domain name, your voice

00:07:58.977 --> 00:08:01.146
app has an invocation name.

00:08:01.179 --> 00:08:04.149 align:start position:0%
The invocation name is how
Google and Amazon know that the

00:08:04.182 --> 00:08:06.719
user wants to talk
to your voice app.

00:08:06.752 --> 00:08:09.121
You'll want to own
your invocation name.

00:08:09.154 --> 00:08:11.991 align:start size:97% position:3%
Well, let's look at an example
of a voice app created

00:08:12.024 --> 00:08:13.292
by Capital One.

00:08:13.325 --> 00:08:16.061
Here's a screenshot from
the Capital One website.

00:08:16.094 --> 00:08:18.163 align:start size:94% position:6%
Notice they're promoting the
Capital One voice

00:08:18.196 --> 00:08:19.999
app to their customers.

00:08:20.032 --> 00:08:23.035
I actually got a Capital One
credit card just to be able to

00:08:23.068 --> 00:08:24.670
use their voice app.

00:08:24.703 --> 00:08:27.840
Now, by using the Capital One
voice app, I don't need to sit

00:08:27.873 --> 00:08:30.309 align:start size:88% position:13%
at my computer and
log into their website.

00:08:30.342 --> 00:08:33.812 align:start position:0%
What if I could just ask for
what I need and let the computer

00:08:33.845 --> 00:08:35.681
do all the work for me?

00:08:35.714 --> 00:08:39.118 align:start size:91% position:9%
Check this out: Alexa, ask
Capital One what

00:08:39.151 --> 00:08:41.020
my credit card balance is.

00:08:41.053 --> 00:08:46.325 align:start position:0%
Alexa: Your current Quicksilver
card balance is $1,227.44.

00:08:46.358 --> 00:08:48.761 align:start size:84% position:16%
Do you want to know
when this bill is due?

00:08:48.794 --> 00:08:50.129
Chip: Yes, please.

00:08:50.162 --> 00:08:51.997 align:start size:91% position:9%
Alexa: The payment of your
Quicksilver card is due

00:08:52.030 --> 00:08:53.999
March 17, 2020.

00:08:54.032 --> 00:08:55.701
Do you want to pay now?

00:08:55.734 --> 00:08:57.002
Chip: No, thank you.

00:08:57.035 --> 00:08:58.203
Alexa: No problem.

00:08:58.236 --> 00:09:00.906 align:start size:97% position:3%
Chip: You probably noticed
that the Capital One voice app

00:09:00.939 --> 00:09:04.710
not only answered my question
about my credit card balance,

00:09:04.743 --> 00:09:08.013
but it assumed that I probably
wanted to know when my balance

00:09:08.046 --> 00:09:11.850
was due, so it asked me, and it
even asked if I wanted to pay my

00:09:11.883 --> 00:09:15.287
credit card bill, all
just by using my voice.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:17.923 align:start size:97% position:3%
But what if I'm looking for
something specific like recent

00:09:17.956 --> 00:09:22.027 align:start position:0%
transactions or how much I
spent at a particular merchant?

00:09:22.060 --> 00:09:24.263
Well, all I have to do is ask.

00:09:24.296 --> 00:09:28.968
Alexa, ask Capital One what
my recent transactions are.

00:09:29.001 --> 00:09:32.605 align:start position:0%
Alexa: Between April 30 and
May 30, you have 17 transactions

00:09:32.638 --> 00:09:36.408
for a total of $535.63.

00:09:36.441 --> 00:09:43.949
It looks like you also had a
credit of $218.49; $72.15 at

00:09:43.982 --> 00:09:49.121 align:start size:97% position:3%
Harris Teeter on May 27,
followed by $19.28 at Circle K

00:09:49.154 --> 00:09:54.093
on May 27, and $4.88 at
Harris Teeter on May 26.

00:09:54.126 --> 00:09:56.128
Would you like to hear more?

00:09:56.161 --> 00:09:57.396
Chip: That's all.

00:09:57.429 --> 00:09:59.231 align:start size:84% position:16%
Alexa: Good
talking to you today.

00:09:59.264 --> 00:10:01.133 align:start size:81% position:19%
Chip: Okay, or
how about this one.

00:10:01.166 --> 00:10:06.305 align:start size:97% position:3%
Alexa, ask Capital One how
much I paid to CVS last month.

00:10:06.338 --> 00:10:09.041 align:start size:91% position:9%
Alexa: Between April 1 and
April 30, you spent a

00:10:09.074 --> 00:10:12.978
total of $187.85.

00:10:13.011 --> 00:10:15.714 align:start size:97% position:3%
Chip: Okay, now voice
technology is still advancing.

00:10:15.747 --> 00:10:20.953
It's still in its early phases,
but the capabilities are growing

00:10:20.986 --> 00:10:22.755
exponentially right now.

00:10:22.788 --> 00:10:26.892
So while the voice app is the
presentation layer, obviously

00:10:26.925 --> 00:10:30.329 align:start size:97% position:3%
the information is coming
from the Capital One systems.

00:10:30.362 --> 00:10:33.232 align:start size:94% position:6%
So I'm not sure what time
zone you're in, but in North

00:10:33.265 --> 00:10:36.402 align:start size:94% position:6%
Carolina, it's supper
time, so let's order pizza.

00:10:36.435 --> 00:10:40.139
Pepperoni, jalapeño, and extra
cheese are my favorite toppings.

00:10:40.172 --> 00:10:42.908
You might not know this about
me, but I live a little bit

00:10:42.941 --> 00:10:46.712
outside the city, in the
country on a little farm.

00:10:46.745 --> 00:10:49.782
It's close enough to the city to
be able to commute in, but it's

00:10:49.815 --> 00:10:53.485
far enough that I'm outside the
delivery zone for Domino's, but

00:10:53.518 --> 00:10:55.788
that doesn't stop me
from ordering a pizza.

00:10:55.821 --> 00:10:57.322
I just have to go pick it up.

00:10:57.355 --> 00:11:02.861
Since I have an Alexa wearable
and Alexa auto--and actually,

00:11:02.894 --> 00:11:05.264
I've got Google and stuff like
that too, but, anyway, I can

00:11:05.297 --> 00:11:09.268 align:start size:97% position:3%
actually start driving to
Domino's and say, "Alexa, I'd

00:11:09.301 --> 00:11:12.738 align:start size:84% position:16%
like to order a
pizza from Domino's."

00:11:12.771 --> 00:11:15.240
Alexa: What type of crust
do you want for your pizza?

00:11:15.273 --> 00:11:18.711
You can choose hand-tossed,
gluten-free crust, Brooklyn

00:11:18.744 --> 00:11:22.014
style, hand-made pan,
or crunchy-thin crust.

00:11:22.047 --> 00:11:23.916
Chip: Crunchy-thin crust.

00:11:23.949 --> 00:11:25.784
Alexa: What size would you
like for your crunchy-thin

00:11:25.817 --> 00:11:27.086
crust pizza?

00:11:27.119 --> 00:11:29.254
You can choose medium or large.

00:11:29.287 --> 00:11:30.856
Chip: Large.

00:11:30.889 --> 00:11:32.825 align:start size:91% position:9%
Alexa: I've got a
large, thin, cheese pizza.

00:11:32.858 --> 00:11:35.394
What toppings would
you like with that?

00:11:35.427 --> 00:11:38.163 align:start size:88% position:13%
Chip:
Pepperoni and jalapeños.

00:11:38.196 --> 00:11:41.233 align:start position:0%
Alexa: Okay,
pepperoni and jalapeño peppers.

00:11:41.266 --> 00:11:43.469 align:start size:84% position:16%
Would you like any
more toppings on that?

00:11:43.502 --> 00:11:45.838
Chip: Extra cheese, please.

00:11:45.871 --> 00:11:48.307
Alexa: Okay, I've added
a large, thin pizza with

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:52.411
pepperoni, jalapeño peppers,
and extra cheese to your order.

00:11:52.444 --> 00:11:54.279
What would you like next?

00:11:54.312 --> 00:11:56.148
Chip: I'd like
to check out now.

00:11:56.181 --> 00:11:58.117 align:start position:0%
Alexa: Would you like to
complete your order by adding a

00:11:58.150 --> 00:12:02.821 align:start size:84% position:16%
16-piece Parmesan
Bread Bites for $3.99?

00:12:02.854 --> 00:12:04.323
Chip: No, thank you.

00:12:04.356 --> 00:12:06.358
Alexa: Your order
contains one pizza.

00:12:06.391 --> 00:12:10.362 align:start size:81% position:19%
The total is
$18.24, after taxes.

00:12:10.395 --> 00:12:13.365 align:start size:97% position:3%
Would you like to review your
order details, or are

00:12:13.398 --> 00:12:15.033
you ready to check out?

00:12:15.066 --> 00:12:17.002
Chip: I'm ready to check out.

00:12:17.035 --> 00:12:18.837
Alexa: Your order should be
ready for pickup in about

00:12:18.870 --> 00:12:20.773
12 to 22 minutes.

00:12:20.806 --> 00:12:22.541
Do you want me to
place the order?

00:12:22.574 --> 00:12:24.209
Chip: Yes.

00:12:24.242 --> 00:12:26.178
Alexa: Okay, I've
placed your order.

00:12:26.211 --> 00:12:28.881
Your day just got cheesier.

00:12:28.914 --> 00:12:30.549 align:start size:91% position:9%
Chip: Notice how they walk
me through the entire

00:12:30.582 --> 00:12:32.117
process of ordering a pizza.

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:35.487
They even tried to up-sell
me for the cheesy sticks.

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:39.224
Anyway, I think it was actually
quicker than pulling out my cell

00:12:39.257 --> 00:12:41.894 align:start size:94% position:6%
phone and finding the number
for Domino's and

00:12:41.927 --> 00:12:43.395
talking to a real person.

00:12:43.428 --> 00:12:46.398 align:start size:97% position:3%
And since it takes me about
15 minutes to get to Domino's,

00:12:46.431 --> 00:12:47.666
perfect timing.

00:12:47.699 --> 00:12:50.469
I can get in my car and head out
there, and it was gonna be ready

00:12:50.502 --> 00:12:51.937
when I got there.

00:12:51.970 --> 00:12:54.239
So many of you listen to
podcasts, or maybe you

00:12:54.272 --> 00:12:55.841
were a podcaster.

00:12:55.874 --> 00:13:00.913
How easy is it for you to listen
to a historical podcast or try

00:13:00.946 --> 00:13:03.916 align:start position:0%
to let people know, "Here's how
to listen to this podcast

00:13:03.949 --> 00:13:06.485 align:start size:97% position:3%
that I did in the past that's
got the information

00:13:06.518 --> 00:13:07.719
that you're looking for"?

00:13:07.753 --> 00:13:12.057
In this "Audio Banding" podcast
by Jodi Krangle, she has a lot

00:13:12.090 --> 00:13:16.562 align:start position:0%
of great information, but
episodes 35 and 36 are actually

00:13:16.595 --> 00:13:20.199
her most important episodes, and
you'll see why in just a second.

00:13:20.232 --> 00:13:23.368
Jodi's invocation name
is "Audio Branding."

00:13:23.401 --> 00:13:27.005 align:start position:0%
What if you could listen to
any past episode just by saying

00:13:27.038 --> 00:13:31.610 align:start size:97% position:3%
something like, "Okay, Google,
ask 'Audio Branding'

00:13:31.643 --> 00:13:35.080
to play episode 35."

00:13:35.113 --> 00:13:37.583
Google Assistant: Got it.
Getting "Audio Branding."

00:13:37.616 --> 00:13:44.890
♪♪♪

00:13:44.923 --> 00:13:46.458 align:start size:88% position:13%
Jodi Krangle: Welcome to
"Audio Branding," the

00:13:46.491 --> 00:13:48.360
hidden gem of marketing.

00:13:48.393 --> 00:13:50.062
I'm your host, Jodi Krangle.

00:13:50.095 --> 00:13:52.097
In this podcast, we'll
discuss just how sound

00:13:52.130 --> 00:13:53.999
influences our behavior.

00:13:54.032 --> 00:13:57.202
I generally talk about this in
the context of advertising and

00:13:57.235 --> 00:14:00.572
marketing, but there are other
places this is important too.

00:14:00.605 --> 00:14:03.508
I really feel that it plays a
much more important role in our

00:14:03.541 --> 00:14:09.648
lives than maybe we realize,
so let's delve a little deeper.

00:14:09.681 --> 00:14:13.886 align:start position:0%
This is the first part of
my interview with Chip Edwards.

00:14:13.919 --> 00:14:16.288 align:start position:0%
Whether you like it or
not, smart speakers like Amazon

00:14:16.321 --> 00:14:19.057
Alexa are used by
millions of people.

00:14:19.090 --> 00:14:21.293
The same voice-assistant
technology found in smart

00:14:21.326 --> 00:14:24.396 align:start size:88% position:13%
speakers is also used in
smartphones, cars,

00:14:24.429 --> 00:14:26.265
wearables, and more.

00:14:26.298 --> 00:14:28.634 align:start position:0%
Voice assistants are everywhere,
and they're changing

00:14:28.667 --> 00:14:30.502
how people consume content.

00:14:30.535 --> 00:14:33.472
Amazon and Google have made a
way for you to register your

00:14:33.505 --> 00:14:35.641
brand on these voice assistants.

00:14:35.674 --> 00:14:39.544
My guest today is technologist
and teacher Chip Edwards, and

00:14:39.577 --> 00:14:42.180 align:start position:0%
he's spoken across the
country about the opportunities

00:14:42.213 --> 00:14:45.684
available on this new platform
and how you can own and manage

00:14:45.717 --> 00:14:48.153
your verbal brand on
these new devices.

00:14:48.186 --> 00:14:51.223 align:start size:91% position:9%
The future is here, and
we're gonna talk about it.

00:14:51.256 --> 00:14:53.025 align:start size:88% position:13%
Thanks for
joining me today, Chip.

00:14:53.058 --> 00:14:54.126
I really appreciate it.

00:14:54.159 --> 00:14:57.129 align:start size:94% position:6%
Chip: Okay, so now you know
why episodes 35 and 36

00:14:57.162 --> 00:14:58.697
are her most important episodes.

00:14:58.730 --> 00:15:03.702 align:start size:91% position:9%
It just happened to be the
ones that I was on for.

00:15:03.735 --> 00:15:08.040
So, but let's--so audio is
already relatively easy to be

00:15:08.073 --> 00:15:13.979 align:start position:0%
able to put on to smart speakers
and digital voice assistants,

00:15:14.012 --> 00:15:15.647
but let's look at this one here.

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:18.116 align:start size:91% position:9%
Many of you
actually know Aida Correa.

00:15:18.149 --> 00:15:22.387
In addition to being a
fantastic speaker, she's

00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:24.489
got a wonderful blog.

00:15:24.522 --> 00:15:26.992 align:start size:97% position:3%
So what if you could listen to
her blog posts while

00:15:27.025 --> 00:15:28.760
you were commuting to work?

00:15:28.793 --> 00:15:32.698
Aida's voice app connects to her
WordPress website and makes her

00:15:32.731 --> 00:15:34.666
blog posts available.

00:15:34.699 --> 00:15:38.570
Let's start her voice app by
using her invocation name,

00:15:38.603 --> 00:15:40.205
"Love Built Life."

00:15:40.238 --> 00:15:43.742
Alexa, start "Love Built Life."

00:15:43.775 --> 00:15:45.544
Alexa: Welcome to
"Love Built Life."

00:15:45.577 --> 00:15:48.146 align:start size:88% position:13%
There is a new blog post
available, titled

00:15:48.179 --> 00:15:51.450 align:start position:0%
"The Joy of Overcoming: A Decade
in Retrospect, Part Two."

00:15:51.483 --> 00:15:54.119 align:start size:88% position:13%
Would you like to
hear the new blog post?

00:15:54.152 --> 00:15:55.420
Chip: Yes.

00:15:55.453 --> 00:15:57.356 align:start position:0%
Alexa: "I didn't bring
you on this journey of the last

00:15:57.389 --> 00:16:00.258 align:start size:94% position:6%
ten years of my life to
give all the gloom and doom.

00:16:00.291 --> 00:16:04.429 align:start position:0%
No, sir, because you've seen the
last few years of this decade

00:16:04.462 --> 00:16:08.333
that has been a turnaround in
my situation and my friends.

00:16:08.366 --> 00:16:11.136 align:start size:97% position:3%
She met a nice young man at
work, and they are now engaged

00:16:11.169 --> 00:16:13.438
to be married, yay."

00:16:13.471 --> 00:16:15.107 align:start size:88% position:13%
Chip: And the blog post
goes on, and it

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:16.408
would've read it for you.

00:16:16.441 --> 00:16:18.343
I'm just doin' the first
piece of each of these

00:16:18.376 --> 00:16:19.544
pieces of content.

00:16:19.577 --> 00:16:23.582
So the point is that she can
continue to write blog posts

00:16:23.615 --> 00:16:27.119 align:start size:97% position:3%
like she likes to do, but now
anyone can listen to

00:16:27.152 --> 00:16:29.287
them just by asking.

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:33.525
So William Jackson has been a
WordCamp speaker and supporter

00:16:33.558 --> 00:16:34.793
all over the place.

00:16:34.826 --> 00:16:36.361 align:start size:84% position:16%
I've run into him in I
don't know how many

00:16:36.394 --> 00:16:38.397
different WordCamps.

00:16:38.430 --> 00:16:41.266 align:start size:91% position:9%
He's also a prolific
blogger with content that

00:16:41.299 --> 00:16:43.301
everybody should hear.

00:16:43.334 --> 00:16:45.370 align:start size:75% position:25%
Read, hear?
Both, actually.

00:16:45.403 --> 00:16:48.173
William wanted to add some
character to his blog posts

00:16:48.206 --> 00:16:51.710
though, so not only does his
voice app connect up with his

00:16:51.743 --> 00:16:55.781 align:start size:97% position:3%
WordPress website, but instead
of having the default smart

00:16:55.814 --> 00:16:59.651
speaker voice read his blog
post, his sound is different.

00:16:59.684 --> 00:17:03.688
William's blog and invocation
name is "My Quest to Teach."

00:17:03.721 --> 00:17:05.323
So let's ask for it.

00:17:05.356 --> 00:17:10.829
Alexa, ask "My Quest to Teach"
to play the latest blog post.

00:17:10.862 --> 00:17:14.066 align:start size:94% position:6%
Alexa: This is blog post 77,
and it's titled "Using

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:17.569
WordPress to Share Your Voice
and Address Social Issues."

00:17:17.602 --> 00:17:20.272 align:start position:0%
Brian: "'Using WordPress
to Share Your Voice and Address

00:17:20.305 --> 00:17:24.709 align:start size:94% position:6%
Social Issues,' instructor,
William Jackson, M.Ed.

00:17:24.742 --> 00:17:27.879 align:start size:97% position:3%
Intro: there is a growing need
for content creators from

00:17:27.912 --> 00:17:31.516
diverse backgrounds to tell
their stories, to share their

00:17:31.549 --> 00:17:34.453
experiences and to encourage
the need and acceptance for

00:17:34.486 --> 00:17:38.523 align:start size:97% position:3%
diversity in using the ability
to speak, write, teach, and

00:17:38.556 --> 00:17:41.693
deliver transformative content."

00:17:41.726 --> 00:17:44.563 align:start size:97% position:3%
Chip: So he had a different
voice, actually, read his blog

00:17:44.596 --> 00:17:48.867
post, and it's all done--this
is all automatic, and matter of

00:17:48.900 --> 00:17:52.604 align:start size:97% position:3%
fact, these audio clips
were done earlier in the year.

00:17:52.637 --> 00:17:56.708 align:start position:0%
They actually just, both Google
and Amazon, upgraded their

00:17:56.741 --> 00:18:00.645
text-to-speech synthesis
process, so the voices are

00:18:00.678 --> 00:18:03.815 align:start size:84% position:16%
actually getting
significantly better.

00:18:03.848 --> 00:18:05.917
Anyway, let's look at one more.

00:18:05.950 --> 00:18:08.220
So I write a blog as well.

00:18:08.253 --> 00:18:12.858
I use my blog posts to not just
write about voice technology but

00:18:12.891 --> 00:18:16.228
to demonstrate some
of the possibilities.

00:18:16.261 --> 00:18:19.331
So my invocation name is "Create
My Voice," and what you're about

00:18:19.364 --> 00:18:22.934
to hear is me asking my
smart speaker to play one

00:18:22.967 --> 00:18:24.636
of my past blog posts.

00:18:24.669 --> 00:18:27.906 align:start size:97% position:3%
And just to prep you,
you're going to hear the voice

00:18:27.939 --> 00:18:31.910 align:start position:0%
assistant whisper, use different
English-speaking voices, and

00:18:31.943 --> 00:18:35.480 align:start size:91% position:9%
even use voices from other
languages, all from

00:18:35.513 --> 00:18:37.215
within my blog post.

00:18:37.248 --> 00:18:39.251 align:start size:91% position:9%
And in a minute, I'm gonna
show you, kind of,

00:18:39.284 --> 00:18:41.219
how some of that is done.

00:18:41.252 --> 00:18:44.556
And so I'm gonna actually have
it read my entire blog post.

00:18:44.589 --> 00:18:47.192
It takes two or three minutes,
somethin' like that, so we've

00:18:47.225 --> 00:18:48.960
got a few minutes for it.

00:18:48.993 --> 00:18:54.432
So let's listen to my blog post
get read by a smart speaker.

00:18:54.465 --> 00:18:59.571 align:start size:94% position:6%
Alexa, ask Create My
Voice to read blog post 27.

00:18:59.604 --> 00:19:01.273
Alexa: Let's get started.

00:19:01.306 --> 00:19:04.976 align:start position:0%
This blog post is titled,
"Bringing Life to Your Content."

00:19:05.009 --> 00:19:09.881
Greetings, I'm Alexa, Amazon's
smart speaker voice assistant.

00:19:09.914 --> 00:19:12.551 align:start size:97% position:3%
With a little help from Create
My Voice, I can read

00:19:12.584 --> 00:19:14.519
your blog posts aloud.

00:19:14.552 --> 00:19:17.455
Now your audience can listen
to your blog posts while making

00:19:17.488 --> 00:19:20.458 align:start size:88% position:13%
breakfast, working
out, or driving to work.

00:19:20.491 --> 00:19:22.294
It's really easy.

00:19:22.327 --> 00:19:24.796
The Create My Voice team
connects me up to your blog

00:19:24.829 --> 00:19:28.967 align:start position:0%
posts using your RSS feed
and a custom voice application.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:32.270
This means that you can keep
blogging like you always have

00:19:32.303 --> 00:19:35.240
and take advantage of the
new smart-speaker platform.

00:19:35.273 --> 00:19:37.809 align:start position:0%
Your audience will ask for your
blog by name, and I'll

00:19:37.842 --> 00:19:39.511
read your latest post.

00:19:39.544 --> 00:19:42.881
I can read your older posts as
well, and I've heard this is

00:19:42.914 --> 00:19:46.551
available on Google devices,
including every Android device

00:19:46.584 --> 00:19:47.819
on the planet.

00:19:47.852 --> 00:19:51.523
But since I'm an Amazon Alexa,
you didn't hear that from me.

00:19:51.556 --> 00:19:54.426
In addition to just reading your
blog, I can help you bring life

00:19:54.459 --> 00:19:55.760
to your blog.

00:19:55.793 --> 00:19:58.396 align:start size:84% position:16%
If I was going to tell
you a secret--

00:19:58.429 --> 00:19:59.931 align:start size:91% position:9%
[whispering]
I would whisper it to you.

00:19:59.964 --> 00:20:01.633
[speaking at normal volume]
But even cooler than that,

00:20:01.666 --> 00:20:02.801
I can change my voice.

00:20:02.834 --> 00:20:06.438 align:start position:0%
This might be difficult to
describe, so let me demonstrate.

00:20:06.471 --> 00:20:08.240
I have several friends.

00:20:08.273 --> 00:20:10.508 align:start size:84% position:16%
I'll have them
introduce themselves.

00:20:10.541 --> 00:20:12.577 align:start size:94% position:6%
[speaking in British accent]
Brian: My name is Brian.

00:20:12.610 --> 00:20:15.914
If it's not clear, I'm
from across the pond.

00:20:15.947 --> 00:20:18.550
[speaking in American accent]
Joanna: Hi, my name is Joanna.

00:20:18.583 --> 00:20:20.619
I'm really glad
to meet you here.

00:20:20.652 --> 00:20:23.355 align:start size:94% position:6%
[speaking in Indian accent]
Raveena: Greetings,
my name is Raveena.

00:20:23.388 --> 00:20:26.858 align:start position:0%
I'm also available to read
all or part of your blog posts.

00:20:26.891 --> 00:20:28.960
Alexa: I told you
it was pretty cool.

00:20:28.993 --> 00:20:31.997
Being able to use multiple
voices in your blog posts can

00:20:32.030 --> 00:20:34.633
bring your blog posts to life
in a world where your audience

00:20:34.666 --> 00:20:36.968
wants to listen instead of read.

00:20:37.001 --> 00:20:40.538
In addition to multiple English
voices, I can also speak using

00:20:40.571 --> 00:20:42.374
voices from other languages.

00:20:42.407 --> 00:20:46.645
I'll show you by greeting you
in French, Spanish, and German.

00:20:46.678 --> 00:20:48.880
First, a male French voice.

00:20:48.913 --> 00:20:50.348
Mathieu: Bonjour.

00:20:50.381 --> 00:20:57.055
[speaking French]

00:20:57.088 --> 00:20:59.424 align:start size:84% position:16%
Alexa: Next, a
female Spanish voice.

00:20:59.457 --> 00:21:04.796 align:start size:78% position:22%
Conchita:
[speaking Spanish]

00:21:04.829 --> 00:21:06.898 align:start size:97% position:3%
Alexa: And,
finally, a male German voice.

00:21:06.931 --> 00:21:14.339
Hans: [speaking German]

00:21:14.372 --> 00:21:16.875
Alexa: Pretty cool,
don't you think?

00:21:16.908 --> 00:21:19.577
Like the additional English
voices, these are available

00:21:19.610 --> 00:21:21.813 align:start size:91% position:9%
to bloggers to expand how
you communicate

00:21:21.846 --> 00:21:23.448
through your blog posts.

00:21:23.481 --> 00:21:26.985
This concludes the post titled
"Bringing Life to Your Content."

00:21:27.018 --> 00:21:29.721
Would you like to hear the next
blog post titled "How Does Voice

00:21:29.754 --> 00:21:32.023
Technology Work,
An Introduction"?

00:21:32.056 --> 00:21:33.558
Chip: No, that's all.

00:21:33.591 --> 00:21:34.759
Alexa: Thank you.

00:21:34.792 --> 00:21:37.629 align:start size:97% position:3%
Chip: So what I wanted to
demonstrate there is that this

00:21:37.662 --> 00:21:44.869
idea of being able to take our
content and make it available or

00:21:44.902 --> 00:21:49.474 align:start size:97% position:3%
present our brand is--there's
a lot of stuff that

00:21:49.507 --> 00:21:50.942
could happen in that space.

00:21:50.975 --> 00:21:54.979 align:start position:0%
So while you can go to my
website and read my blog posts,

00:21:55.012 --> 00:21:57.549
sometimes it's more
informative or fun to

00:21:57.582 --> 00:21:59.017
actually listen to them.

00:21:59.050 --> 00:22:02.654 align:start size:97% position:3%
But you're probably wondering
how that magic happens.

00:22:02.687 --> 00:22:07.459 align:start position:0%
So similar to HTML tags, there's
a standard set of tags that

00:22:07.492 --> 00:22:11.029
provide directions to the
text-to-speech process.

00:22:11.062 --> 00:22:15.367
It's called SSML, or Speech
Synthesis Markup Language.

00:22:15.400 --> 00:22:17.469
Let me show you one of the tags.

00:22:17.502 --> 00:22:20.905
So here's an excerpt out
of one of my blog posts.

00:22:20.938 --> 00:22:27.045
Looks pretty standard, but
let me pull up the source.

00:22:27.078 --> 00:22:31.850
So you'll notice there's a new
tag that I've embedded into the

00:22:31.883 --> 00:22:35.787
blog post, a voice tag.

00:22:35.820 --> 00:22:39.023
There's that one, and then
there's that one right there.

00:22:39.056 --> 00:22:42.761 align:start size:84% position:16%
So let's listen to how
Amazon Alexa turns

00:22:42.794 --> 00:22:46.164
this text into speech.

00:22:46.197 --> 00:22:48.600
Alexa: "'Alexa
and the Elderly.'

00:22:48.633 --> 00:22:51.669
Comments from participants.

00:22:51.702 --> 00:22:55.006
This first commenter shares
how Alexa opened her world."

00:22:55.039 --> 00:22:57.041 align:start size:97% position:3%
Raveena: "I thought
Alexa was just for things like

00:22:57.074 --> 00:23:00.478
turning on lights, but it
opened a whole new world.

00:23:00.511 --> 00:23:02.914
You can do anything
that you want to do."

00:23:02.947 --> 00:23:05.784 align:start position:0%
Alexa: "And this last comment
references how using Alexa helps

00:23:05.817 --> 00:23:08.019 align:start size:88% position:13%
someone with
physical difficulties."

00:23:08.052 --> 00:23:09.854 align:start size:84% position:16%
Brian: "I
have a genetic tremor.

00:23:09.887 --> 00:23:12.624
So entering data is a pain.

00:23:12.657 --> 00:23:15.693 align:start size:97% position:3%
The ability to speak a command
and get something to happen

00:23:15.726 --> 00:23:18.496
is a wonderful thing."

00:23:18.529 --> 00:23:23.168 align:start position:0%
Chip: So notice that my blog
post looks like any blog post or

00:23:23.201 --> 00:23:27.205
a excerpt out of my blog post
here, but when it gets turned

00:23:27.238 --> 00:23:35.213
into speech, we can bring life
to our blog posts or to any of

00:23:35.246 --> 00:23:40.718
our written content as we use
these voice assistants to be

00:23:40.751 --> 00:23:44.889
able to communicate
with our audience.

00:23:44.922 --> 00:23:47.892 align:start size:97% position:3%
So normally, that's where I
would stop, but I've got a few

00:23:47.925 --> 00:23:51.229
more minutes, and so I've got
some bonus material for you.

00:23:51.262 --> 00:23:54.232 align:start size:97% position:3%
So I've used that term
"invocation name" a number of

00:23:54.265 --> 00:23:58.102 align:start size:97% position:3%
times, so let's--I wanna
dig into it just a little bit

00:23:58.135 --> 00:24:00.905 align:start size:97% position:3%
because there are some
interesting nuances with this

00:24:00.938 --> 00:24:03.074
idea of an invocation name.

00:24:03.107 --> 00:24:06.177
So with our websites, one of the
first things that we think about

00:24:06.210 --> 00:24:10.248 align:start position:0%
is choosing a good domain
name that represents our brand.

00:24:10.281 --> 00:24:14.052 align:start position:0%
Now, in 1995, we could just
use our brand name as our domain

00:24:14.085 --> 00:24:17.555 align:start size:91% position:9%
name, but it's not
quite that simple anymore.

00:24:17.588 --> 00:24:20.892
Matter of fact, sometimes we
pick our domain name first, and

00:24:20.925 --> 00:24:25.029
then that's how we decide what
our brand name is, but getting a

00:24:25.062 --> 00:24:28.933 align:start size:94% position:6%
good domain name now is a
little bit more challenging.

00:24:28.966 --> 00:24:31.936 align:start size:97% position:3%
But when we think about the
voice-assistant world, we have

00:24:31.969 --> 00:24:35.640 align:start size:91% position:9%
to have to think
about sounds, not sights.

00:24:35.673 --> 00:24:37.308
So let me explain what I mean.

00:24:37.341 --> 00:24:41.279
Let's say that I'm really good
at giving my two cents out to

00:24:41.312 --> 00:24:47.151
everyone I meet, and I am, but
anyway, so, but, obviously, I

00:24:47.184 --> 00:24:51.789
would want to build a website
and get the domain name of

00:24:51.822 --> 00:24:54.058
"TwoCents," right?

00:24:54.091 --> 00:24:56.294
So let's say I could get the
domain name at "TwoCents."

00:24:56.327 --> 00:24:58.029
Okay, I'm good.

00:24:58.062 --> 00:25:03.768
But what about this domain
name of "Two-Cents.com"?

00:25:03.801 --> 00:25:07.906
Or "2Cents.com,"
with the number 2?

00:25:07.939 --> 00:25:14.212
Or "ToCents.com," spelled T-O
Cents instead of T-W-O, or

00:25:14.245 --> 00:25:16.848
T-O-O Cents.com.

00:25:16.881 --> 00:25:20.952
And that's not even addressing
the idea of, you know, the "dot

00:25:20.985 --> 00:25:23.788 align:start size:81% position:19%
org," the "dot net,"
"dot ai," "dot--"

00:25:23.821 --> 00:25:26.291 align:start size:88% position:13%
all the other top-level
domains out there.

00:25:26.324 --> 00:25:30.995
So when we think about branding,
and we think about "I'm building

00:25:31.028 --> 00:25:35.099 align:start position:0%
a website, I need a domain
name," we think kind of visually

00:25:35.132 --> 00:25:40.004
when we look at that, but when
we look at the verbal side of

00:25:40.037 --> 00:25:44.676 align:start size:97% position:3%
it, how many different ways
are there to say, "Two Cents"?

00:25:44.709 --> 00:25:48.646 align:start position:0%
Well, there's only one way of
being able to make the sounds of

00:25:48.679 --> 00:25:53.351
"two cents," and this was just
the "Two Cents" with "Cents"

00:25:53.384 --> 00:25:58.256
spelled C-E-N-T-S, but what
about the "Two Cents" when we

00:25:58.289 --> 00:26:00.758
use a different form of "Cents"?

00:26:00.791 --> 00:26:04.729
Or the other form of "Cents"?

00:26:04.762 --> 00:26:08.232
And so, in other words, when we
look at this, we have this idea

00:26:08.265 --> 00:26:12.136
of this collision that happens
because sometimes in the visual

00:26:12.169 --> 00:26:17.308
world, we think that "Here's my
brand," but when we go to the

00:26:17.341 --> 00:26:21.045
audio world, sometimes we have
these collisions, and so who's

00:26:21.078 --> 00:26:26.851
gonna own the voice app that's
connected with the invocation

00:26:26.884 --> 00:26:29.153
name of "Two Cents"?

00:26:29.186 --> 00:26:33.758
So how that works is, with
Amazon, what they did is they

00:26:33.791 --> 00:26:38.663
said, "Okay, we're gonna let
multiple voice apps have the

00:26:38.696 --> 00:26:41.199 align:start size:94% position:6%
same domain name or the same
invocation name,

00:26:41.232 --> 00:26:42.433
same verbal domain name."

00:26:42.467 --> 00:26:46.904
It causes some confusion because
now the user has to figure out

00:26:46.937 --> 00:26:50.074
which version of "Two Cents"
did they want because there's

00:26:50.107 --> 00:26:51.976
multiple of 'em out there.

00:26:52.009 --> 00:26:53.745
Google went the other way.

00:26:53.778 --> 00:26:57.248
They went the same way
that the domain name is.

00:26:57.281 --> 00:27:00.752
They said the first person that
builds that Google action or the

00:27:00.785 --> 00:27:04.389 align:start size:97% position:3%
voice app in the Google
voice-assistant world, they're

00:27:04.422 --> 00:27:09.927
the ones that whoever does that
now owns the verbal version of

00:27:09.960 --> 00:27:11.796
the sounds "Two Cents."

00:27:11.829 --> 00:27:16.167 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, in that case, it's
kind of like 1995 right now.

00:27:16.200 --> 00:27:21.272 align:start position:0%
You can get your invocation
name, but the first person that

00:27:21.305 --> 00:27:24.676
gets it is gonna own it, and
they're gonna be the ones that

00:27:24.709 --> 00:27:28.246
decide what is that dialogue
that happens whenever somebody

00:27:28.279 --> 00:27:31.449
invokes that invocation name
of "Two Cents" or whatever

00:27:31.482 --> 00:27:33.284
your brand name is.

00:27:33.317 --> 00:27:36.954 align:start position:0%
So that's one of the things that
you wanna think about in the

00:27:36.987 --> 00:27:42.960 align:start position:0%
idea of verbal branding of--your
domain name or your verbal

00:27:42.993 --> 00:27:45.997
domain name is somethin' that
you're gonna wanna look at, you

00:27:46.030 --> 00:27:49.133 align:start size:94% position:6%
know, I would suggest
sooner as opposed to later.

00:27:49.166 --> 00:27:52.937
Before, we were usin' the
domain--or the invocation

00:27:52.970 --> 00:27:54.405
name of Capital One.

00:27:54.438 --> 00:27:55.673 line:0%
Let's look at that one, even.

00:27:55.706 --> 00:28:00.078 line:0%
So if I'm thinkin' about Capital
One, CapitalOne.com, right, and

00:28:00.111 --> 00:28:03.815 line:0%
they probably own that name,
but there's multiple ways of

00:28:03.848 --> 00:28:08.886 line:0%
spelling "Capital," and there's
multiple ways of spelling "One,"

00:28:08.919 --> 00:28:15.226 line:0%
and even words that sound like
"One" or close enough that you

00:28:15.259 --> 00:28:18.162 line:0%
might not be able to--the voice
assistant might not be able to

00:28:18.195 --> 00:28:21.432 line:0%
pick up the difference between
the sounds, and so, when you

00:28:21.465 --> 00:28:26.003 line:0%
register for an invocation name,
you're actually registering for

00:28:26.036 --> 00:28:29.841 line:0%
the sounds that happen, not
the spelling that happens.

00:28:29.874 --> 00:28:33.411 align:start size:94% position:6%
Okay, so let's start to
finish up with a quote here.

00:28:33.444 --> 00:28:37.181
Britt Armour from Clearbridge
Mobile wrote that "Voice is the

00:28:37.214 --> 00:28:41.052
future for how brands are gonna
interact with their customers."

00:28:41.085 --> 00:28:45.223
So let me do a quick recap
before we get to questions.

00:28:45.256 --> 00:28:48.760
Voice assistant technology means
that the visually impaired don't

00:28:48.793 --> 00:28:52.463 align:start position:0%
have to figure out how to
navigate a sighted world because

00:28:52.496 --> 00:28:56.200 align:start size:97% position:3%
we're using computers to shift
the cognitive load from

00:28:56.233 --> 00:28:59.003
the user to the computer.

00:28:59.036 --> 00:29:02.240
This is a transformational
mind-set shift, and it's

00:29:02.273 --> 00:29:06.844 align:start size:97% position:3%
changing how we think
about user-interface designs.

00:29:06.877 --> 00:29:10.381 align:start size:97% position:3%
We're changing our UI/UX from
"How can we make

00:29:10.414 --> 00:29:13.050
computers easy to use?

00:29:13.083 --> 00:29:17.288 align:start size:94% position:6%
How can I put a good
user-interface design so the

00:29:17.321 --> 00:29:20.958 align:start size:91% position:9%
user can figure out how to
find what he wants or

00:29:20.991 --> 00:29:22.527
how to do what he wants?"

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:27.064 align:start size:94% position:6%
we're changing that to "How
can we make computers--

00:29:27.097 --> 00:29:31.936
or how can we use computers to
make it easy to get stuff done?"

00:29:31.969 --> 00:29:35.072
So we're shifting the cognitive
load from the user having to

00:29:35.105 --> 00:29:40.011 align:start position:0%
figure out how to make something
happen, to the user just says

00:29:40.044 --> 00:29:43.548 align:start position:0%
what he wants, and the computer
has to figure out what that

00:29:43.581 --> 00:29:47.919 align:start position:0%
user's intention is or what that
user wants to happen, and now

00:29:47.952 --> 00:29:51.055 align:start size:81% position:19%
the computer
performs the action.

00:29:51.088 --> 00:29:53.524 align:start size:97% position:3%
And so we're shiftin' the
cognitive load off of the user

00:29:53.557 --> 00:29:57.361
and onto the computers, and
that's a change in how we

00:29:57.394 --> 00:29:59.130
actually design systems.

00:29:59.163 --> 00:30:02.066
And you'll see that change, not
just in voice assistants, but

00:30:02.099 --> 00:30:05.436
you'll see it in chatbots and
stuff like that where a good

00:30:05.469 --> 00:30:08.206
chatbot or a good voice
assistant is movin' that

00:30:08.239 --> 00:30:12.610
cognitive load off of the user,
into the compute space, and to

00:30:12.643 --> 00:30:17.849 align:start size:97% position:3%
be able to do more work, which
is a good thing, but it's a

00:30:17.882 --> 00:30:21.953 align:start size:91% position:9%
mental shift for us
developers and designers.

00:30:21.986 --> 00:30:25.323 line:68%
And then there's one final tip
that I wanna leave you with, and

00:30:25.356 --> 00:30:28.960 line:68%
that's I would suggest that you
consider getting your brand's

00:30:28.993 --> 00:30:32.496 line:68%
invocation name sooner as
opposed to later while it's

00:30:32.529 --> 00:30:35.066 align:start position:0% line:68%
still relatively easy to get
them because there's not a whole

00:30:35.099 --> 00:30:38.502 line:68%
lot of voice apps out there
right now, but companies are

00:30:38.535 --> 00:30:41.272 align:start size:97% position:3% line:68%
doin'--there's a lot of
companies actually workin' to

00:30:41.305 --> 00:30:44.509 line:68%
build their presence
on these voice devices.

00:30:45.009 --> 00:30:47.178 line:0%
Okay, so here's my
contact information.

00:30:47.211 --> 00:30:49.313 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
I love talkin'
about voice technology.

00:30:49.346 --> 00:30:52.483 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
I'm available for strategy
sessions, special engagements,

00:30:52.516 --> 00:30:55.586 align:start position:0% line:0%
and how I can build a voice
app with your invocation name so

00:30:55.619 --> 00:30:58.522 line:0%
that you can start usin'
this new platform as well.

00:30:58.555 --> 00:31:00.458 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
And that's what I have for
you today, and see

00:31:00.491 --> 00:31:01.959 line:0%
if there's any questions.

00:31:01.992 --> 00:31:03.461 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
David: There
totally are questions, Chip.

00:31:03.494 --> 00:31:05.329 line:0%
Thank you so much.
That was awesome.

00:31:05.362 --> 00:31:08.299 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
We'll go ahead and
start with the first one.

00:31:08.332 --> 00:31:10.501 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
Get my video going there.
Hello, everyone.

00:31:10.534 --> 00:31:14.205 align:start position:0% line:0%
All right, first question, "What
practical applications in the

00:31:14.238 --> 00:31:19.076
accessibility space that we'll
see first in terms of this smart

00:31:19.109 --> 00:31:22.246
speaker technology or
is in place already?

00:31:22.279 --> 00:31:26.918
So what practical applications
in the accessibility space that

00:31:26.951 --> 00:31:31.355
we'll see first in terms of
smart speaker technology?

00:31:31.388 --> 00:31:37.194 align:start position:0%
Chip: So there's two ways
that this can happen because you

00:31:37.227 --> 00:31:41.198
noticed the first--what I was
tryin' to demonstrate is the

00:31:41.231 --> 00:31:46.737
idea that now people can just
ask for what they want, and as

00:31:46.770 --> 00:31:51.375
the voice apps are built out
more, now the computers are

00:31:51.408 --> 00:31:53.945 align:start size:94% position:6%
actually figuring that
out and responding to them.

00:31:53.978 --> 00:31:57.081
So instead of having a screen
scraper go through and read

00:31:57.114 --> 00:31:59.617
through a website and try
to find different pieces of

00:31:59.650 --> 00:32:04.455
information and leave all that
work on the visually impaired to

00:32:04.488 --> 00:32:07.558 align:start position:0%
figure out "How can I find
what I want, and how can I make

00:32:07.591 --> 00:32:10.061 align:start size:84% position:16%
things happen?"--
very, very difficult.

00:32:10.094 --> 00:32:11.329
I mean, they're good at it.

00:32:11.362 --> 00:32:14.465
I've seen some of the visually
impaired actually use some of

00:32:14.498 --> 00:32:20.037
those screen readers, and
it's amazing, actually.

00:32:20.070 --> 00:32:24.408 align:start size:97% position:3%
But we're still putting the
cognitive load on them, and we

00:32:24.441 --> 00:32:29.180 align:start size:97% position:3%
try to remind people, as
they're building their website

00:32:29.213 --> 00:32:33.484
interfaces, to do a good job to
make it so that it's relatively

00:32:33.517 --> 00:32:37.521
easy for the screen readers to
get the information, but we're

00:32:37.554 --> 00:32:41.492 align:start position:0%
still leavin' the cognitive load
on the user, on the visually

00:32:41.525 --> 00:32:43.761 align:start size:84% position:16%
impaired, to be
able to do that work.

00:32:43.794 --> 00:32:47.431 align:start position:0%
Voice technology changes that
all on its head because now they

00:32:47.464 --> 00:32:51.268
can just ask for what
they want and get it.

00:32:51.301 --> 00:32:55.272
We're moving that cognitive
load into the compute space.

00:32:55.305 --> 00:32:57.141
And it also does
the other thing.

00:32:57.174 --> 00:33:04.115
I actually was in a conference
earlier this year, and there was

00:33:04.148 --> 00:33:10.321
somebody that actually did a
presentation, and she wasn't

00:33:10.354 --> 00:33:14.225
able to speak, but
she was able to type.

00:33:14.258 --> 00:33:20.398
And so what she did is that she
put her whole presentation in a

00:33:20.431 --> 00:33:24.268
written form and then used voice
technology to turn that written

00:33:24.301 --> 00:33:29.640 align:start position:0%
form into audio so that we
could all listen to what she was

00:33:29.673 --> 00:33:34.045 align:start position:0%
trying to communicate, and
with this new technology and the

00:33:34.078 --> 00:33:37.114
different tools with SSML and
stuff like that, it's actually

00:33:37.147 --> 00:33:40.084 align:start size:94% position:6%
making it so that she can
actually bring a lot of life

00:33:40.117 --> 00:33:42.486
into what she's communicating.

00:33:42.519 --> 00:33:46.123 align:start position:0%
And so I see this voice
technology kind of happening in

00:33:46.156 --> 00:33:51.162 align:start position:0%
both sides of it and really
helping those with accessibility

00:33:51.195 --> 00:33:58.502
needs to be able to--it's now
their world that we're playing

00:33:58.535 --> 00:34:03.507
in as opposed to them havin'
to play in the sighted world or

00:34:03.540 --> 00:34:08.212 align:start size:88% position:13%
those of us who
don't have those needs.

00:34:08.245 --> 00:34:10.681 align:start size:97% position:3%
David: That was really--it
struck--it stood out for me as

00:34:10.714 --> 00:34:15.252
you were playing those Alexa
examples how different and more

00:34:15.285 --> 00:34:18.856 align:start position:0%
purpose-built the content
sounded than what you would hear

00:34:18.889 --> 00:34:21.525
from a screen reader,
reading a web page.

00:34:21.558 --> 00:34:24.728
So my next question is, you
know, how should people think

00:34:24.761 --> 00:34:27.098
about creating their
content for voice?

00:34:27.131 --> 00:34:28.699
Should it be specific?

00:34:28.732 --> 00:34:30.835
I know you kind of showed the
example of someone, just, kind

00:34:30.868 --> 00:34:34.205 align:start position:0%
of, feeding the blog through,
but I'm guessing you're thinking

00:34:34.238 --> 00:34:39.510 align:start position:0%
about the context of the content
related to, you know, voice,

00:34:39.543 --> 00:34:41.779
specifically, when
you're leveraging it.

00:34:41.812 --> 00:34:43.547
Is that true, or how
do you think of that?

00:34:43.580 --> 00:34:46.584
Chip: That's actually a
really good point, and

00:34:46.617 --> 00:34:51.288 align:start size:97% position:3%
actually, a really big area to
talk about because

00:34:51.321 --> 00:34:53.324
there's two sides to that.

00:34:53.357 --> 00:34:59.530
One of 'em is "How can I make
sure my content is in a form

00:34:59.563 --> 00:35:04.335
that represents my brand, and
when it gets converted into

00:35:04.368 --> 00:35:08.906 align:start position:0%
audio when people listen to it,
how can it represent

00:35:08.939 --> 00:35:10.140
my brand well?

00:35:10.174 --> 00:35:12.676
How do I write well, how do I
make sure my heading tags--"

00:35:12.709 --> 00:35:16.413 align:start size:94% position:6%
because I can make something
look good on my website

00:35:16.446 --> 00:35:19.483
that doesn't turn into
audio very well at all.

00:35:19.516 --> 00:35:24.889
But the other side of that is,
lots of times, in our websites,

00:35:24.922 --> 00:35:29.426
we think of monolithic text in
long form, and we're expecting

00:35:29.459 --> 00:35:32.930
especially with somebody using a
screen reading to have to jump

00:35:32.963 --> 00:35:36.233 align:start position:0%
through all that to find what
they're looking for, and when we

00:35:36.266 --> 00:35:41.505
think about actually preparing
stuff for voice assistants, we

00:35:41.538 --> 00:35:45.643 align:start position:0%
now need to think of how do I
put this content in a capsulized

00:35:45.676 --> 00:35:50.581 align:start position:0%
form so that people can ask
for the piece that they want as

00:35:50.614 --> 00:35:55.452 align:start position:0%
opposed to entire, long-form
piece of it and have them listen

00:35:55.485 --> 00:35:57.755
to the whole thing to be able
to figure out what they want?

00:35:57.788 --> 00:36:00.791
And so it does change how you
actually think about putting

00:36:00.824 --> 00:36:05.596
your content together and where
you store it and how you store

00:36:05.629 --> 00:36:08.432
it and stuff like that, so, yes.

00:36:08.465 --> 00:36:09.900 align:start size:75% position:25%
David: Awesome.
Thank you.

00:36:09.933 --> 00:36:11.602 align:start size:84% position:16%
Chip: Good
stuff to think about.

00:36:11.635 --> 00:36:13.637
David: Yeah, you showed some
examples of Alexa reading the

00:36:13.670 --> 00:36:16.440 align:start position:0%
content and different
accents with different genders.

00:36:16.473 --> 00:36:19.009 align:start position:0%
I know certainly a lot of people
here at Accessibility Today

00:36:19.042 --> 00:36:22.846 align:start position:0%
strive to be inclusive of those
that represent their brand.

00:36:22.879 --> 00:36:24.815
How do you think about
the choice of voice?

00:36:24.848 --> 00:36:28.319
Do brands typically choose a
voice, or will they vary it

00:36:28.352 --> 00:36:29.587
based on the author?

00:36:29.620 --> 00:36:33.524
Or I don't know if you've given
much thought to diversity as it

00:36:33.557 --> 00:36:38.429 align:start size:94% position:6%
relates to the voice that
you choose for your content?

00:36:38.462 --> 00:36:41.332 align:start size:91% position:9%
Chip: So that's a good
question, and from a brand

00:36:41.365 --> 00:36:44.935 align:start position:0%
perspective, there's kind
of--there's a wide range of that

00:36:44.968 --> 00:36:48.405
because you've got from the
simple of "I'm just using the

00:36:48.438 --> 00:36:53.410
default reader," whatever that
is, and in some cases, like, I

00:36:53.443 --> 00:36:56.814
think, Google is pretty good
at letting the user choose what

00:36:56.847 --> 00:37:00.684
voice they want to be able
to hear their content in.

00:37:00.717 --> 00:37:03.287
So there's--that's a good thing.

00:37:03.320 --> 00:37:07.591
But when you think about the
ability to use those voice tags

00:37:07.624 --> 00:37:11.662
and be able to, kind of, add
some differentiation in your

00:37:11.695 --> 00:37:16.500
content, so there's some
opportunities there, and as

00:37:16.533 --> 00:37:19.403 align:start position:0%
you're--what I tried to do is
saying, okay, "Here, we're gonna

00:37:19.436 --> 00:37:23.040
read back and forth, and we're
gonna use different ethnicities

00:37:23.073 --> 00:37:24.975
to be able to read content, to
be able to add some additional

00:37:25.008 --> 00:37:30.714
diversity and an interest into
a blog post," but then, from a

00:37:30.747 --> 00:37:35.519
branding perspective, you can
actually even go as far as--I

00:37:35.552 --> 00:37:40.591
think it was KFC, that they
actually recorded their own

00:37:40.624 --> 00:37:47.364
voice, Colonel Sanders's voice,
and they have a whole set of

00:37:47.397 --> 00:37:51.568 align:start position:0%
specific for their brand, their
voice models, and now they

00:37:51.601 --> 00:37:52.802
can do the same thing.

00:37:52.836 --> 00:37:56.440 align:start size:97% position:3%
They can put in their text,
and it gets converted into the

00:37:56.473 --> 00:38:00.377
Colonel Sanders's voice, using
that voice model, and it could

00:38:00.410 --> 00:38:01.845
be very brand specific.

00:38:01.878 --> 00:38:05.015
So there's a wide range but
definitely something to think

00:38:05.048 --> 00:38:08.552
about as you're looking at
diversity of making sure that

00:38:08.585 --> 00:38:12.089
you're not just saying,
"Hey, I want this US

00:38:12.122 --> 00:38:15.959
male to read all of my content."

00:38:15.992 --> 00:38:17.594
It's something that you can
think about 'cause there's

00:38:17.627 --> 00:38:21.899 align:start size:94% position:6%
multiple US male voices and
female voices and other

00:38:21.932 --> 00:38:24.735 align:start size:97% position:3%
English voices, and then other
language voices as well.

00:38:24.768 --> 00:38:27.471 align:start size:97% position:3%
I mean, there's lots of
opportunities there to be able

00:38:27.504 --> 00:38:30.574 align:start size:91% position:9%
to demonstrate
diversity in your content.

00:38:30.607 --> 00:38:32.609
David: Yeah, I'm sure it gets
tricky when you start thinking

00:38:32.642 --> 00:38:34.978 align:start position:0%
about the voice
representing the author as well.

00:38:35.011 --> 00:38:36.447
Chip: Right.

00:38:36.480 --> 00:38:37.615
David: Thank you for that.

00:38:37.648 --> 00:38:39.416 align:start size:94% position:6%
All right, next question,
"What types of smart-speaker

00:38:39.449 --> 00:38:42.052 align:start size:97% position:3%
automations will most benefit
the Ally community that

00:38:42.085 --> 00:38:43.654
you can share with us?"

00:38:43.687 --> 00:38:46.357
So what is, you know, most
exciting for you, for how it

00:38:46.390 --> 00:38:49.660 align:start size:88% position:13%
will support the Ally
community accessibility?

00:38:49.693 --> 00:38:56.533 align:start position:0%
Chip: So, for me, the biggest
excitement in this space is this

00:38:56.566 --> 00:39:03.640
idea of design-thinking shifts
because a lot of us, when we

00:39:03.673 --> 00:39:09.513
think of UI/UX, we're really
thinking about "How can I build

00:39:09.546 --> 00:39:14.151 align:start position:0%
this for a sighted person on my
site to be able to

00:39:14.184 --> 00:39:16.487
navigate my site well?"

00:39:16.520 --> 00:39:20.190 align:start size:91% position:9%
And lots of times, it's a
secondary thought of,

00:39:20.223 --> 00:39:21.658
"Oh, wait a minute.

00:39:21.691 --> 00:39:24.862
What if--how can I support
somebody that's visually

00:39:24.895 --> 00:39:27.164
impaired of some way?"

00:39:27.197 --> 00:39:30.934 align:start position:0%
And, "Okay, how much effort am I
willing to go into, to be

00:39:30.967 --> 00:39:33.504
able to accommodate that?"

00:39:33.537 --> 00:39:37.574
Because my sighted design
is really important to me.

00:39:37.607 --> 00:39:40.844
I like my sliding windows and
all that kind of stuff that

00:39:40.877 --> 00:39:44.982
sometimes give grief to, you
know, those who are visually

00:39:45.015 --> 00:39:49.486 align:start size:91% position:9%
impaired, but it's--and so
it's a balance of

00:39:49.519 --> 00:39:51.855
"Which do I want more?"

00:39:51.888 --> 00:39:56.093
I think that the opportunities
in the voice space though kind

00:39:56.126 --> 00:39:59.863 align:start size:94% position:6%
of turns that on its head
from the perspective of "I'm

00:39:59.896 --> 00:40:07.671
designing for all of my audience
the same now because, if I have

00:40:07.704 --> 00:40:13.243
to build this system that nobody
is seeing, the sighted part is

00:40:13.276 --> 00:40:17.080
secondary, and all of
it is audio up front.

00:40:17.113 --> 00:40:23.220 align:start position:0%
How can I accommodate everybody,
not just a sighted person?"

00:40:23.253 --> 00:40:25.789
Matter of fact, the first time
I did one of my talks, somebody

00:40:25.822 --> 00:40:30.561
came up to me afterwards, and he
said, "You just did this fancy

00:40:30.594 --> 00:40:34.531 align:start position:0%
new technology, smart-speaker
world talk, but really, it was a

00:40:34.564 --> 00:40:38.635 align:start size:84% position:16%
diversity talk in
disguise, wasn't it?"

00:40:38.668 --> 00:40:43.106
Because we talked about this
idea of "How do I present my

00:40:43.139 --> 00:40:49.680
information in such a way that
everybody is gonna get the same

00:40:49.713 --> 00:40:51.949
experience out of it?"

00:40:51.982 --> 00:40:54.618 align:start position:0%
David: I think that's a great
observation, that paradigm shift

00:40:54.651 --> 00:40:59.189 align:start position:0%
towards voice and kind of
being assistive in that sense of

00:40:59.222 --> 00:41:02.693 align:start size:91% position:9%
getting brands on
board with accessibility.

00:41:02.726 --> 00:41:04.161
Next question-- 

00:41:04.194 --> 00:41:05.596
Chip: Now, just
one more comment.

00:41:05.629 --> 00:41:07.531
David: Oh, yeah, please.

00:41:07.564 --> 00:41:13.504 align:start size:97% position:3%
Chip: Now, and I--
want to say it again--is voice

00:41:13.537 --> 00:41:17.274
technology doesn't solve
all accessibility issues.

00:41:17.307 --> 00:41:22.045 align:start position:0%
It does solve some accessibility
issues, and it makes us think

00:41:22.078 --> 00:41:25.716
about how we can deliver our
content or engage with our

00:41:25.749 --> 00:41:32.122
audience in a way that supports
accessibility, but it's not--it

00:41:32.155 --> 00:41:34.758
doesn't solve all
of our problems.

00:41:34.791 --> 00:41:39.630 align:start position:0%
It's just a tool, a platform
that helps us get out of some of

00:41:39.663 --> 00:41:46.069
our mind-set of "I'm supporting
this set of people, and now,

00:41:46.102 --> 00:41:49.306 align:start size:94% position:6%
wait a minute, I should
also help these people too.

00:41:49.339 --> 00:41:52.242
How can I do that without
messing up my cool stuff?"

00:41:52.275 --> 00:41:55.178
It makes it so that, no, you're
building cool stuff that happens

00:41:55.211 --> 00:42:00.317
to be for everybody, not
just by sighted people.

00:42:00.350 --> 00:42:02.586 align:start size:94% position:6%
David: That's a
great point of distinction.

00:42:02.619 --> 00:42:04.054
Thank you so much.

00:42:04.087 --> 00:42:07.057
Next question is
from Amber Hines.

00:42:07.090 --> 00:42:09.826 align:start position:0%
Hey, Amber.
I know you from around the way.

00:42:09.859 --> 00:42:14.231
"How do voice tags impact the
experience for users on screen

00:42:14.264 --> 00:42:18.635
readers like NVDA,
JAWS, and VoiceOver?

00:42:18.668 --> 00:42:23.740
Do they read those tags
or just ignore them?"

00:42:23.773 --> 00:42:26.376 align:start size:94% position:6%
Chip: So I don't know
the answer to that question.

00:42:26.409 --> 00:42:31.114
I do know that those voice tags
and some of the other SSML tags,

00:42:31.147 --> 00:42:35.719 align:start position:0%
they're a set standard, so it's
not like, "Oh, this is

00:42:35.752 --> 00:42:37.688
only done for smart speakers."

00:42:37.721 --> 00:42:41.658 align:start position:0%
It's a set of standard tags,
and there's actually quite a few

00:42:41.691 --> 00:42:44.361
tags that you can do a lot
of different things with.

00:42:44.394 --> 00:42:51.702
So my assumption is that a good,
well-rounded screen reader would

00:42:51.735 --> 00:42:54.104
use those tags in a way.

00:42:54.137 --> 00:42:59.209 align:start position:0%
I do know that the voice
assistants use the--accommodate

00:42:59.242 --> 00:43:07.217
the--some or a lot of the SSML
tags and in--to varying degrees.

00:43:07.250 --> 00:43:10.087 align:start size:97% position:3%
Like, Amazon, I did the Amazon
examples on purpose because

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:14.358 align:start position:0%
Amazon supports almost all of
the SSML tags, and so I was able

00:43:14.391 --> 00:43:16.994 align:start size:97% position:3%
to do the voice
switching and stuff like that.

00:43:17.027 --> 00:43:21.231 align:start position:0%
Google doesn't support the
voice tag yet, so they're still

00:43:21.264 --> 00:43:24.635 align:start size:91% position:9%
building out that tag, but
they support most of

00:43:24.668 --> 00:43:26.403
the other SSML tags.

00:43:26.436 --> 00:43:29.940
So my assumption is yes, they
would either ignore it, and/or

00:43:29.973 --> 00:43:33.844
they would be able to handle
them, but I don't know enough.

00:43:33.877 --> 00:43:35.912 align:start position:0%
I haven't experimented with
them to be able to say for sure.

00:43:35.945 --> 00:43:37.447 align:start size:94% position:6%
David: Thank you, thank you;
if you know the answer,

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:39.116
maybe you can post it
in a YouTube chat and--

00:43:39.149 --> 00:43:40.417 align:start size:81% position:19%
Chip: There you go.
That'd be good.

00:43:40.450 --> 00:43:42.719 align:start size:75% position:25%
David: List
an answer there.

00:43:42.752 --> 00:43:48.692 align:start position:0%
Chip, I think you probably
spurred a invocation name, like,

00:43:48.725 --> 00:43:52.095
rush, like, the domain rushes
when they would release the new

00:43:52.128 --> 00:43:55.032
TLDs, and, like, everyone would
go register all these domains.

00:43:55.065 --> 00:43:57.834
I feel like that last slide of
yours really probably got some

00:43:57.867 --> 00:43:59.803
people off their rear and
were, you know, Googling

00:43:59.836 --> 00:44:01.838
how to figure that out.

00:44:01.871 --> 00:44:04.041
Have you experienced--you
mentioned how not a lot of

00:44:04.074 --> 00:44:06.243
people that are leveraging the
invocation names, but have you

00:44:06.276 --> 00:44:09.379
experienced yet when a brand
has an invocation name that's

00:44:09.412 --> 00:44:13.116
already claimed, that's, like,
their brand and that kind of

00:44:13.149 --> 00:44:17.020
fight that we see over
the domain name space?

00:44:17.053 --> 00:44:24.728
Chip: So, I--how do
I answer that right?

00:44:24.761 --> 00:44:30.333
So what I can say is that to be
able to get an invocation name,

00:44:30.366 --> 00:44:34.137
you have to build a voice app
and have it certified by the

00:44:34.170 --> 00:44:41.211
respective party, either Amazon
or Google or Samsung or--and in

00:44:41.244 --> 00:44:44.815
that certification process is
when they say, "Okay, yes, your

00:44:44.848 --> 00:44:48.218
voice app is certified, and
that invocation name works

00:44:48.251 --> 00:44:49.319
for your voice app."

00:44:49.352 --> 00:44:51.455
And in Google's case, it's
like, "Okay, you now own

00:44:51.488 --> 00:44:55.158
that invocation name."

00:44:55.191 --> 00:45:00.063
What I have seen is--matter of
fact, I had one of my clients

00:45:00.096 --> 00:45:04.935 align:start size:97% position:3%
call me up the other day,
and he's a podcaster, and when

00:45:04.968 --> 00:45:07.170 align:start size:97% position:3%
people were asking for his
podcast, which is "What's your

00:45:07.203 --> 00:45:10.941 align:start size:97% position:3%
Excuse"--there's a
multiple "What's Your Excuse"

00:45:10.974 --> 00:45:16.913
podcasts out there, and Amazon
was choosing somebody else's

00:45:16.946 --> 00:45:19.316
"What's Your Excuse"
podcast by default.

00:45:19.349 --> 00:45:21.952 align:start size:94% position:6%
And so he said, "Hey,
what can we do about that?"

00:45:21.985 --> 00:45:25.922
Well, we can build a voice app,
and we can use the invocation

00:45:25.955 --> 00:45:28.859
name of "What's Your Excuse"
and so now when people say,

00:45:28.892 --> 00:45:31.995 align:start size:94% position:6%
"Play 'What's Your Excuse,'"
Amazon says, "Oh, hey,

00:45:32.028 --> 00:45:33.864
there's a voice app
out there with the

00:45:33.897 --> 00:45:35.432 align:start size:88% position:13%
invocation name, 'What's
Your Excuse.'

00:45:35.465 --> 00:45:40.403
We'll use that to decide what
content should be delivered."

00:45:40.436 --> 00:45:43.073
And so now, when you say, "Play
'What's Your Excuse'" on the

00:45:43.106 --> 00:45:47.544
Amazon devices, his podcast gets
played instead of Amazon getting

00:45:47.577 --> 00:45:51.181
to decide who--whatever
one they wanna play.

00:45:51.214 --> 00:45:56.386 align:start position:0%
So the answer is yes, the
invocation name is gonna kind of

00:45:56.419 --> 00:45:58.955
change thing on its head.

00:45:58.988 --> 00:46:03.460
Very, very few people know that
this invocation name is gonna be

00:46:03.493 --> 00:46:07.364
a really big deal in the
voice assistant space.

00:46:07.397 --> 00:46:10.367
And so that's usually
at the end of my talk.

00:46:10.400 --> 00:46:12.002 align:start size:97% position:3%
That's one of the big things,
it's like, "Okay, wait

00:46:12.035 --> 00:46:13.603
a minute, so what do I do?

00:46:13.636 --> 00:46:20.577
Because I got a brand, and
I wanna manage that," so-- 

00:46:20.610 --> 00:46:22.879
David: It doesn't sound
like SEO is dying, Chip.

00:46:22.912 --> 00:46:24.147
Chip: No, no.

00:46:24.180 --> 00:46:25.415 align:start size:81% position:19%
David: Feel like
SEO is here to stay.

00:46:25.448 --> 00:46:26.616
Well, this was amazing.

00:46:26.649 --> 00:46:29.352 align:start position:0%
I learned so much from this
presentation, thank you so much.

00:46:29.385 --> 00:46:31.454 align:start position:0%
Chip: You're absolutely welcome.
Thank you for havin' me.

00:46:31.487 --> 00:46:34.624
This was--it was great to
talk, and good questions.

00:46:34.657 --> 00:46:35.858
I appreciate 'em.

00:46:35.892 --> 00:46:37.861
David: Yeah, thank you, thank
you, I have a little history

00:46:37.894 --> 00:46:39.629 align:start size:94% position:6%
of voice, so I had wanted to
nerd all out on it,

00:46:39.662 --> 00:46:42.098 align:start position:0%
but I wish we had
more time, but thank you all for

00:46:42.131 --> 00:46:45.235 align:start size:97% position:3%
attending this session
with Chip Edwards and myself.

